{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012ysRMH9wtQCWfasUKfvWXs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"ES logs to stdout (Console appender), not to files. This means Filebeat needs to read from the container's stdout. This is typically done by reading from `/var/log/containers/` or using Kubernetes log collection approach.\n\nHowever, for sidecar-based monitoring, Filebeat reads from the pod's container logs which are on the host at `/var/log/containers/`. But inside the pod sidecar, it can't access the host's filesystem by default.\n\nActually, in Kubernetes, container logs go to stdout and are accessible on the host at `/var/log/containers/`. \n\nFor a sidecar pattern to work, I need either ES to log to files on a shared volume that Filebeat can read, or Filebeat to access the Docker socket with elevated privileges. Since ES currently logs only to stdout, the practical solution is to configure ES to also write to a file by adding a file appender to its log4j2 configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":860,"cache_read_input_tokens":37801,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":860},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8105a4ca-e6a7-429a-b99b-a7586082dad8","uuid":"cae5da8c-754e-495b-8558-388cb7cadd1f","request_id":"req_011CcfvWX1d3poKBuEGSW8bE"}
