{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EbFQhCbnGSFraPeYGL7Fkp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding:\n\n1. ES 8.11.1 is running with TLS and security enabled\n2. Monitoring cluster is ES 7.17.9, no security\n3. ES logs to stdout (Console appender), so Filebeat can't read log files from a shared volume\n4. Available images: `metricbeat:7.17.9`, `filebeat:7.17.9`, `filebeat:8.11.1`\n\nFor the sidecar approach with Filebeat reading ES logs:\n- ES currently logs only to stdout (not files)\n- I can switch from the default `log4j2.properties` to `log4j2.file.properties`, which would enable file-based logging alongside stdout, allowing Filebeat to read logs from a shared emptyDir volume\n- The key is setting `path.logs` in elasticsearch.yml to point to a mounted directory and ensuring the file appenders are active in log4j2.properties, then mounting that same volume to Filebeat so it can tail the logs. 2.properties` file. The setup-keystore init container copies the default config from the image into an emptyDir volume that the main container then mounts, so I need to figure out how to inject a custom log4j2 configuration that writes to files instead of just stdout. Let me trace through the actual volume mounts in the StatefulSet to understand the flow better. Actually, I need to reconsider how Kubernetes volume mounting works here. You can't mount multiple volumes at the same path, but you can mount a ConfigMap subPath to a specific file within a directory that's already mounted by another volume. So I could mount the log4j2.properties file from a ConfigMap directly into the emptyDir-mounted config directory without conflicts.\n\nThe approach would be to keep the emptyDir mounted at the config directory with the init container populating it, then layer a ConfigMap mount on top for just the log4j2.properties file. But I need to think through whether the init container's