decar container so it can verify the connection.\n\nNow I'm planning the implementation: I'll create ConfigMaps for the modified log4j2.properties, Metricbeat config, and Filebeat config, then patch the StatefulSet to add an emptyDir volume for logs, mount the modified log4j2 config in the ES container, and add both Metricbeat and Filebeat sidecars with the necessary secret mounts and volume bindings. But I'm running into an issue with the data PVC being only 5GB, though an emptyDir for logs should be fine. Actually, since Metricbeat will be running as a sidecar in the same pod as Elasticsearch, it can connect directly to localhost:9200 instead of going through the service, which simplifies things. I'm configuring Metricbeat to connect to the local Elasticsearch instance with the elastic credentials and CA certificate, while sending its metrics to the monitoring cluster's Elasticsearch service.\n\nFor Filebeat, I'm setting it up to tail the JSON logs from Elasticsearch and forward them to the monitoring cluster. Now I need to handle the log4j2 configuration—Elasticsearch currently only logs to console, but I need to enable file logging so Filebeat has something to collect.\n\nThe solution is to replace the default `log4j2.properties` with the file-based version that includes both console and file appenders. Since Elasticsearch reads this config from `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/`, I can mount a ConfigMap subPath directly over that file, which should take precedence over the existing one in the volume.\n\nThe init container copies files from the image into `es-config-vol` at `/es-config`, then the main container mounts that same volume at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config`. If I also mount the ConfigMap at the specific file path `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/log4j2.properties`, that ConfigMap file will overlay the one from the volume.\n\nFor the logs, `log4j2.properties` references `${sys:es.logs.base_path}` which comes from `path.logs` in elasticsearch.yml, defaulting to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/`. Since that's just the container's local filesystem, I can either use it directly or add an emptyDir volume if I need to share logs across containers.\n\nThe default `path.logs` is already set to `$ES_HOME/logs`, so I don't need to modify elasticsearch.yml. Now I'm planning out the ConfigMaps I'll need: one for the modified log4j2.properties that enables file logging, one for metricbeat configuration, and one for filebeat configuration.\n\nFor the StatefulSet patch, I need to add three volumes (an emptyDir for logs, plus ConfigMaps for both beat configurations and the log4j2 properties), then add the metricbeat and filebeat containers alongside the main Elasticsearch container. The main ES container will need volumeMounts for the logs directory and the log4j2.properties file using a subPath mount.\n\nSince `es-config-vol` is already mounted at the config directory with the original log4j2.properties, overlaying it with a subPath mount from a ConfigMap will replace just that file. I'll create a new log4j2.properties that keeps the Console appender for kubectl logs visibility while also adding a RollingFile appender to write to the shared logs volume.\n\nThe file will write to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/elasticsearch_server.json` based on the cluster name, which Filebeat can then read from. For the sidecar versions, I'm constrained to use `metricbeat:7.17.9` since there's no 8.11.1 available, though I have both filebeat versions to choose from.\n\nThe key question is whether Metricbeat 7.17.9 can properly monitor Elasticsearch 8.x with security enabled. The `/_monitoring/bulk` API has been stable since ES 6.x, but I need to verify that authentication will work correctly between the older Metricbeat and the newer Elasticsearch instance.\n\nFor the architecture, Metricbeat will read from the ES 8.11.1 cluster running locally and ship those metrics to the separate 7.17.9 monitoring cluster. Now I'm working on the log4j2 configuration to enable file logging with JSON output instead of using the full default properties file. Elasticsearch sets this system property from the `path.logs` configuration before initializing log4j2, so that should work fine. The container runs as user 1000 with an emptyDir mounted at the logs path, which is writable by default. I should also verify the `imagePullPolicy` is set correctly for the locally loaded images—it's `IfNotPresent` which is right for kind. Now let me check whether the metricbeat images are actually loaded in the kind cluster. I should check if the beat images are already loaded into the kind cluster's containerd, and if not, load them there before proceeding with the deployment.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6366,"cache_read_input_tokens":38661,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6366},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8105a4ca-e6a7-429a-b99b-a7586082dad8","uuid":"3260739d-e185-41b2-9ce9-3f03c16f169d","request_id":"req_011CcfvXYQysCC82adAt41Fc"}
